                                                  <li><strong>Outdated information:</strong> Old copyright dates and references to past sales and events can indicate that a website (and consequently a business) is neglected</li>                                                                <li><strong>Look and feel:</strong> An outdated website that looks like it was designed in another decade will give a bad impression for your company brand.</li>                                                                <li><strong>Content is not keeping pace with industry developments: </strong> Referencing a product or practice that is irrelevant, extinct or outdated is the kiss of death for someone evaluating you over your competitors</li>                                                                <li><strong>You are not getting traffic on pertinent keywords:</strong> There are certain keywords that are important to every business.  Your website should get some traffic from some of these.  If you are not, it means that you don't have enough content to capture them.  </li>                                                                <li><strong>You are not capitalizing on the keywords you are getting:</strong>  You are getting traffic from search engines, but you don't have enough content on your site to meet your audience's needs and capitalize on the opportunity.</li>                                                            </ul>		                                                            <p>These days the internet is vital component of every enterprise.  And consumers now use the internet as their primary resource for research service providers.  When consumers can make another choice with a few swipes of a computer mouse, an obsolete website can make your business obsolete. This means that that people leave your business in favor of one of your competitors without you even knowing it. </p>                                                           